On May 28, 1715, the Constitution Club met at the King's Head Tavem in the High Street ‚to celebrate the king's birthday. Before the door they had raised ahuge heap of saggots sor a bonine, in which it was rumoured they intended to burn the effigies os the late Queen Anne os blessed memory, and the Dulce os Ormond, Chancellor os the University. As they were sitting in the hotel and spending the time till dusk should come on, in drinking prosperity to the Royal Family‚ a very numerous mob made a rush on the saggots, and attacked the club-room with brick-bats and stones; Tory gownsmen crowded ' the streets and houses near the tavem, threw up their

¹ caps, and scattered money among the crowd,‘crying

out ‘down ,with the Constitutioners-down with the Whigs-no George-James sor ever, Ormond, Boling- broke. The excited crowd then proceeded to the Presbyterian meeting-house, gutted it, pulled down the greater part of the shell, bumed the pulpit at Carsax, and put the clerk, or ‘Amen-raiser' as they called him, in the stocks. About this time, Mr. Deering, the senior proctor, hearing os the riot, pro- ceeded to the King's Arms and dispersed the club.
